[3
Date: 18 Dec 2000 08:46
Source: M2 Communications Ltd. [edited

SASKATCHEWAN: Starting 1 Jan 2001, Saskatchewan Agriculture and Food is
offering a voluntary surveillance program for Chronic Wasting Disease (CWD)
to Saskatchewan game farmers. "The certificate of participation in this
program will help inspect herds that are in the program. Application forms
will be mailed to game farm producers in January. This new program
complements the expanded 3-year monitoring program, initiated by
Saskatchewan Environment and Resource Management, to determine if chronic
wasting disease is in the province's wild deer and elk populations.
Contact: Dr. Louise Greenberg
Director Inspection and Regulatory
Management Branch Saskatchewan Agriculture and Food Regina
Tel: +1 306 787 6423
[Chuck Fenwick's questions draw an analogy with the BSE situation ongoing
in Europe in terms of the animal feed used for farmed elks as well as a
focus on possible means of transmission of the CWD. A prior posting from
the Canadian Food Inspection Agency mentioned that the CWD in these
affected herds in Canada was felt to be related to imported elk from South
Dakota in 1990, with all cases linked to the original imported
animals. Another prior posting from Dr. Elizabeth Williams of the
University of Wyoming (a leading expert on CWD) mentioned that the captive
animals in which CWD were identified had not been fed UK bone meal, and
that the strains of CWD were different from BSE strains. (see refs 1-6 for
further info).
Kathryn Tominey's question re: advisories for hunters is worthwhile. Even
if we assume hunters know not to eat sick or suspect animals, a warning is
just good public health. In the USA, the Colorado Division of Wildlife
issued an advisory letter in Oct 1996 to hunters to avoid eating meat or
organs from animals with signs of CWD. I vaguely remember reading a
national advisory from the US Fish and Wildlife Agency, but have been
unable to find the exact reference. On reviewing the advisories issued in
both the USA and Canada, most are for hunters to submit suspected
CWD-infected animals for testing. They mentioned that to date there has
been no evidence linking CWD to vCJD, but the hypothetical risk of an
analogous TSE should be considered before eating any animal showing signs
of emaciation. - Mod.MPP
1. Peters J, Miller JM, Jenny AL, Peterson TL, Carmichael KP.
Immunohistochemical diagnosis of chronic wasting disease in preclinically
affected elk from a captive herd. J Vet Diagn Invest. 2000 Nov;12(6):579-82.
2. O'Rourke KI, Besser TE, Miller MW, Cline TF, Spraker TR, Jenny AL, Wild
MA, Zebarth GL, Williams ES. PrP genotypes of captive and free-ranging
Rocky Mountain elk (_Cervus elaphus nelsoni_) with chronic wasting disease.
J Gen Virol. 1999 Oct;80 ( Pt 10):2765-9.
3. Miller MW, Williams ES, McCarty CW, Spraker TR, Kreeger TJ, Larsen CT,
Thorne ET. Epizootiology of chronic wasting disease in free-ranging cervids
in Colorado and Wyoming. J Wildl Dis. 2000 Oct;36(4):676-90.
4. Priola SA. Prion protein and species barriers in the transmissible
spongiform encephalopathies. Biomed Pharmacother. 1999;53(1):27-33. Review.
5. Spraker TR, Miller MW, Williams ES, Getzy DM, Adrian WJ, Schoonveld GG,
Spowart RA, O'Rourke KI, Miller JM, Merz PA. Spongiform encephalopathy in
free-ranging mule deer (_Odocoileus hemionus_), white-tailed deer
(_Odocoileus virginianus_) and Rocky Mountain elk (_Cervus elaphus
nelsoni_) in north central Colorado. J Wildl Dis. 1997 Jan;33(1):1-6.
6. Williams ES, Young S. Spongiform encephalopathies in Cervidae. Rev Sci
Tech. 1992 Jun;11(2):551-67
